item.title: ATM_2025_5410: Addressing information gaps on little penguins to support offshore wind
item.description:
This project seeks to generate targeted information to support decision-making by assessment officers and project proponents under the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 (EPBC Act).  

The research will investigate risks and potential impact pathways to little penguins (Eudyptula minor) arising from offshore wind farms and associated port developments in Australia. The findings will inform effective mitigation and management strategies, enabling regulators and industry to assess renewable energy projects under the EPBC Act with greater speed and scientific rigour. For further details, refer to the associated ATM documentation.

item.title: ATM 2025 2336: Procurement for Cross Divisional Financial and Market Data Services
item.description: DISR requires access to comprehensive, reliable, and real-time financial and market data services to support its policy, research and analytical functions. We seek a data service that provides access to high-quality, real time and historical datasets, analysis and analytical tools to enable evidence-based decision making through an informed understanding of: • domestic and international markets across a range of business entities • economic conditions in Australian industries, including to assess whether the Australian market is, or may experience, injury because of anti-competitive behaviour • the international competitiveness of Australia’s resources and heavy industry sectors in the context of a decarbonising world economy • emerging industry risks. The data service must be delivered through either a desktop browser, a secure online platform, terminal access across multiple locations and/or an API with sufficient functionality to meet the needs of geographically dispersed officers within DISR.

item.title: AII-AIMEP-2501: Provision of the Australia-Indonesia Muslim Exchange Program (AIMEP)
item.description: DFAT is seeking a service provider to design and deliver the annual Australia-Indonesia Muslim Exchange Program (AIMEP) for two years from April 2026 to March 2028. AIMEP is one of the Australian-Indonesia Institute’s (AII) longstanding, annual flagship exchange programs. Established in 2002, AIMEP is an intensive program of intercultural and interreligious exchange that brings together Muslim changemakers, community activists and emerging leaders from across Indonesia and Australia, often with ministerial engagement. Delegates undertake immersion programs in Australia and Indonesia where they experience the other's culture and society and engage with leading academics, religious and community leaders, and government representatives.

item.title: AII-AIYEP-2502: Provision of the Australia-Indonesia Youth Exchange Program (AIYEP)
item.description: DFAT is seeking a service provider to design and deliver the annual Australia-Indonesia Youth Exchange Program (AIYEP) for two years from April 2026 to March 2028. AIYEP is one of the Australian-Indonesia Institute’s (AII) longstanding, annual flagship exchange programs. Established in 1982, AIYEP links Australian and Indonesian youth (aged 21-25) through social, professional, and cultural exchange. Delivered in partnership with Kemenpora, the Indonesian Ministry of Youth and Sport, AIYEP aims to foster mutual understanding and increase cultural literacy and capability. Program delegates grow their intercultural skills and international networks through internships, language training, academic workshops and cultural activities, including undertaking immersion programs in each country.
